## My contribution

I was the product designer on a small working team of:
- 1 PM
- 1 engineer
- 1 designer (me)

My contribution went beyond screens.

I:
- identified the **image-first opportunity**
- helped define how and where **AI should enter the workflow**
- designed the **hover preview interaction**
- worked on **prompt design** alongside my PM
- thought through the **coordinate system and placement logic** for labels
- designed for different **image aspect ratios and sizes**
- worked closely with engineering on implementation details
- later influenced the **V2 auto-placement work** as vision model capabilities improved

This project was one of my earliest examples at Wayground of working not just as a UI designer, but as someone shaping the logic of the system itself: workflow, AI behavior, interaction design, and implementation constraints together.

---

## Hurdles and constraints

This project had real constraints, especially in 2024.

### 1. Vision models were much weaker than they are today
We could not assume reliable, pixel-perfect image understanding or placement.

### 2. Latency mattered
Even when the generation itself worked, the experience could feel slow. We had to design the system to feel responsive and understandable while processing happened in the background.

### 3. Accuracy and hallucination risk
If the system generated wrong labels or implausible questions, teachers would lose trust quickly. We spent a lot of effort on prompt design to improve output quality and reduce hallucinations.

### 4. Label placement was especially hard
One of the most technically interesting problems was figuring out where labels should go.

We initially experimented with a grid-based approach:
- divide the image into a grid
- ask the model to indicate the likely region for each label
- convert that into coordinates for placement

This was conceptually clever, but in 2024 it was not accurate enough to fully trust.

As a result, the initial launch focused on:
- generating the question
- generating the labels
- previewing them
- preserving manual control

Later, in 2026, we improved auto-placement as the underlying capabilities got better.

