---

## What shipped in V1 vs later

### V1 (2024)
- image-first entry into the workflow
- improved discovery of in-product image search
- explicit “no labels” refinement for better image results
- AI-generated question suggestions based on image understanding
- hover preview of generated labels
- editable output after acceptance:
  - rename
  - delete
  - add manually
  - reposition
  - change label orientation

### Later improvements (2026)
- more reliable automatic label placement, enabled by stronger vision capabilities

This split matters because it shows that the workflow redesign itself delivered value even before the underlying placement models became significantly better.

---

## Reflection

This project taught me a few things that still shape how I think about product design:

### 1. Good workflow design often starts by questioning the sequence, not the UI
We could have kept polishing the old editor for much longer. The real unlock came from rethinking where the flow starts.

### 2. AI works best when it is grounded in existing user intent
A prompt box would have been the lazier solution. Using the chosen image as the input made the experience both smarter and simpler.

### 3. Automation needs editability
Trust came not from perfect generation, but from giving teachers a strong starting point while preserving full control.

### 4. Product design sometimes means designing the system, not just the screen
The work here involved interaction design, prompt design, coordinate logic, implementation realities, latency handling, and aspect-ratio behavior — not just layout decisions.

---

## TL;DR

Labeling was a high-value but frustrating premium question type. By recognizing that teachers start with the image — not the question text — we redesigned the flow around an image-first workflow and used AI to generate relevant questions and labels at the right moment. The result was a faster, simpler creation experience that improved save rate substantially and became an early example of workflow-native AI at Wayground.
